				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">What the devil are they thinking? (v1.5 rant)<a name="64032"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 24 04 10:23 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Okay, so yeah, after playing a ranger for a couple years (granted, after the Kunark fiasco), I suppose I have a vague idea about what it means to be ignored by the developers for a long time.
<br />

<br />
But the way they have balanced these new 1.5 epics pissed me off.
<br />

<br />
Why in the name of all that is unholy and evil do beastlords, who have identical offensive skills as we do but already provide far more dps in the form of their pets and because they share monk loot tables, get a massively superior ratio for their weapon? Who the h*ll thought this up? How is balance maintained with WARRIORS getting a &gt;1.0 ratio on the epic? Why the h*ll do knights and beastlords get &gt;1.0 (1h, not speaking about knight epics obviously) ratio weapons to make up for the lack of their offensive skills when bards get this thing? Who the h*ll thought of this? Did they just snicker and go, &quot;Oh, well, they can do all these things in a group, they don't need good weapons.&quot; The h*ll?
<br />

<br />
End rant.
<br />

<br />
I am not expecting something overpowered for the amount of work (though considering the amount of work, I expected something slightly better). It just that compared to other classes, it is amazingly inferior.
<br />

<br />
Why do I always pick the classes that seem to be cared for the least?
<br />

<br />
Edit, some links:
<br />
Beastlord v1.5: <a target="_new" href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/item.html?id=52911">Savage Lord's Totem</a>
<br />
Warrior v1.5: <a target="_new" href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/item.html?id=60321">Champion's Sword of Eternal Power</a>
<br />
Bard v1.5: <a target="_new" href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/item.html?id=77631">Prismatic Dragon Blade</a>
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
